  <main id="main-content">
    <section id="why" class="section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>Why Accountability Matters</h2>
        <p>When projects are paid for with public money, communities deserve transparency, fairness, and quality. Accountability isn’t a burden—it’s the backbone of trust, safety, and value for taxpayers.</p>
        <div class="grid three">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Transparency</h3>
            <p>Clear budgets, change orders, schedules, and decisions should be available for public review.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Fairness</h3>
            <p>Competitive procurement, equal opportunity, and compliance with labor and safety laws protect workers and the public.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Quality & Safety</h3>
            <p>Projects must meet code, deliver promised outcomes, and prioritize community safety and durability.</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="obligations" class="section alt">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>What Public Accountability Includes</h2>
        <ul class="obligations">
          <li><strong>Open Procurement:</strong> Competitive bidding, documented evaluations, and conflict-of-interest disclosures.</li>
          <li><strong>Financial Controls:</strong> Traceable funding sources, auditable budgets, and documented change orders.</li>
          <li><strong>Compliance:</strong> Adherence to building codes, safety standards, labor laws, and contract terms.</li>
          <li><strong>Progress Reporting:</strong> Regular schedule updates, milestones, and KPI tracking accessible to stakeholders.</li>
          <li><strong>Community Engagement:</strong> Public notices, accessible meetings, and clear channels for feedback.</li>
          <li><strong>Record Retention:</strong> Keep procurement, contract, and performance documentation for auditability.</li>
        </ul>
        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>Bottom line:</strong> Accepting public funds creates obligations to the public—transparency, compliance, and performance are non-negotiable.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="checklist" class="section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>Transparency Checklist for Contractors</h2>
        <p>Use this quick checklist to improve accountability practices on publicly funded projects.</p>
        <div class="grid two">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Before Award</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Publish bid documents and prequalification criteria.</li>
              <li>Disclose beneficial ownership and potential conflicts.</li>
              <li>Define KPIs: schedule, cost, quality, safety.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>During Construction</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Maintain a public-facing dashboard with schedule and progress.</li>
              <li>Document change orders with rationale and cost impact.</li>
              <li>Report incidents, inspections, and compliance checks.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>After Completion</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Publish final costs vs. budget and variance analysis.</li>
              <li>Provide as-builts, warranties, and O&amp;M manuals.</li>
              <li>Host a post-project lessons-learned summary.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Governance & Ethics</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Whistleblower channels and non-retaliation policy.</li>
              <li>Third-party audits and corrective action plans.</li>
              <li>Data retention and public records compliance.</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section id="report" class="section alt">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>Report Issues or Request Information</h2>
        <p>Community oversight is vital. Use these pathways to raise concerns or ask for project documentation.</p>
        <div class="grid two">
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Report Concerns</h3>
            <ul>
              <li>Procurement irregularities or bid-rigging</li>
              <li>Unsafe practices or code violations</li>
              <li>Cost overruns without explanation</li>
              <li>Conflict-of-interest or favoritism</li>
            </ul>
            <a class="btn" href="#" aria-disabled="true" title="Customize this link to yourur city/state ethics, inspector general, or public works reporting portal.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="card">
            <h3>Request Records</h3>
            <p>Many jurisdictions provide public records request processes (e.g., FOIA in the U.S.). Ask for:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>Contracts, bids, and evaluation scoring</li>
              <li>Budgets, invoices, and change orders</li>
              <li>Inspection reports and certifications</li>
              <li>Schedules, KPIs, and punch lists</li>
            </ul>
            <a class="btn" href="#" aria-disabled="true" title="Insert your local FOIA/Open Records linkon id="faq" class="section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>FAQ & Myth-Busting</h2>
        <details>
          <summary>“We followed the contract—why does the public need to see our documents?”</summary>
          <p>Contracts funded with public money typically trigger transparency and audit obligations. The public is entitled to understand how funds are used and whether outcomes match commitments.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>“Is competitive bidding always required?”</summary>
          <p>Thresholds and exceptions vary by jurisdiction, but competitive processes and documentation are foundational to fair, accountable procurement.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>“How do we balance proprietary info with transparency?”</summary>
          <p>Sensitive information can be protected consistent with law. However, core records—awards, budgets, change orders, schedules, and compliance—are generally subject to public disclosure.</p>
        </details>
        <details>
          <summary>“Who oversees accountability?”</summary>
          <p>Agencies, auditors, inspectors general, and the public share oversight. Strong governance includes internal controls and independent review.</p>
        </details>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="section cta">
      <div class="container">
        <h2>Taking on public work means taking on public trust.</h2>
        <p>Build transparently, deliver quality, and engage your community. Accountability is how we build better together.</p>
